Korovchinsky ( 1992 )
stated that
D. perarmatum
was of the
D. brachyurum
group. Many records under this name across China are suspect and should be included in biogeographical analysis with great care only. They may refer to any of at least seven other species, with
D. mongolianum
,
D. dubium
and
D. amurensis
the most prominent. Most populations of ‘
D. brachyurum
’ recorded from the Heilong Jiang basin definitely belong to
D. amurensis
Korovchinsky & Sheveleva, 2009
(Kotov et al . 2011 )
.
